</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Magnetic resonance (MR) imaging and computed tomography (CT) can be useful in the diagnosis of biliary disease, with both modalities allowing detailed evaluation of the biliary tract. Careful interrogation of the images is critical, regardless of modality. The identification of dilated bile ducts necessitates evaluation for strictures or filling defects, which is best performed with thin-section imaging. Smooth, concentric short-segment strictures favor a benign cause, whereas abrupt, eccentric long-segment strictures favor a malignancy. At MR imaging, extrabiliary entities such as crossing vessels or metallic clip artifact may mimic strictures and should not be mistaken for disease. A stone is the most common biliary filling defect and may occur in the absence of dilated ducts. Stones commonly have a lamellated, geometric shape and are found in a dependent portion of the duct. Identification of bile duct wall thickening raises concern for cholangitis or malignancy. Improved diagnosis of biliary disease can be achieved with a knowledge of the benefits and limitations of modern MR and CT cholangiographic techniques, including the use of biliary-excreted contrast material and of various postprocessing techniques. Familiarity with the radiologic appearances of the duct lumen, wall, and surrounding structures is also important for accurate image interpretation. The rapidly evolving technology for both MR imaging and CT of the biliary tract will continue to present radiologists with opportunities as well as challenges.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095514">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095514">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g01x.jpeg" height="1474" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f1-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Coronal intravenous contrast-enhanced reformatted image from CT data shows the CBD and CHD (arrowheads), which are normal caliber and have an imperceptible wall. The IBDs are barely visible.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f1-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g10a.jpeg" height="1408" width="1512" aria-labelledby="f10a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> CBD stone. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a normal-appearing nondilated CBD 5 mm in diameter with an imperceptible wall (arrow). The duct lumen demonstrates fluid attenuation. <b>(b)</b> CT scan obtained caudad to <b>a</b> shows a CBD stone (arrow) that is slightly hyperattenuating relative to fluid and is associated with bile duct mural hyperenhancement and thickening.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f10a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g10b.jpeg" height="1498" width="1584" aria-labelledby="f10b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> CBD stone. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a normal-appearing nondilated CBD 5 mm in diameter with an imperceptible wall (arrow). The duct lumen demonstrates fluid attenuation. <b>(b)</b> CT scan obtained caudad to <b>a</b> shows a CBD stone (arrow) that is slightly hyperattenuating relative to fluid and is associated with bile duct mural hyperenhancement and thickening.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f10b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g11a.jpeg" height="1477" width="1602" aria-labelledby="f11a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> CBD stones. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a mildly dilated CBD with a lamellated 6-mm stone in a dependent location (arrow). A crescent of lower-attenuation bile (arrowhead) is seen anterior to the stone. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained in a different patient shows a normal-caliber CBD with a stone in the dependent portion of the duct (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f11a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g11b.jpeg" height="1317" width="1404" aria-labelledby="f11b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> CBD stones. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a mildly dilated CBD with a lamellated 6-mm stone in a dependent location (arrow). A crescent of lower-attenuation bile (arrowhead) is seen anterior to the stone. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained in a different patient shows a normal-caliber CBD with a stone in the dependent portion of the duct (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f11b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g12a.jpeg" height="1482" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f12a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Bile duct mural enhancement associated with cholecystitis and cholangitis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal reformatted image from contrast-enhanced CT data obtained for the staging of gastric cancer shows the gallbladder with a normal thin wall (arrow) and a nondilated CBD with an imperceptible wall (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Repeat CT scan obtained 1 week later for abdominal pain shows interval thickening of the gallbladder wall with pericholecystic fat stranding (arrow), findings that indicate cholecystitis, as well as new mural thickening and enhancement of the CHD (arrowhead) and IBDs, findings that indicate cholangitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f12a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g12b.jpeg" height="1338" width="1620" aria-labelledby="f12b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Bile duct mural enhancement associated with cholecystitis and cholangitis. <b>(a)</b> Coronal reformatted image from contrast-enhanced CT data obtained for the staging of gastric cancer shows the gallbladder with a normal thin wall (arrow) and a nondilated CBD with an imperceptible wall (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Repeat CT scan obtained 1 week later for abdominal pain shows interval thickening of the gallbladder wall with pericholecystic fat stranding (arrow), findings that indicate cholecystitis, as well as new mural thickening and enhancement of the CHD (arrowhead) and IBDs, findings that indicate cholangitis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f12b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g13a.jpeg" height="1704" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f13a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> CBD stone. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a hypointense stone in the dependent portion of the CBD (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On a corresponding fat-saturated gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image, the stone (arrow) is hyperintense. The stone was shown to be a pigment stone.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f13a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g13b.jpeg" height="1660" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f13b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> CBD stone. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows a hypointense stone in the dependent portion of the CBD (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On a corresponding fat-saturated gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image, the stone (arrow) is hyperintense. The stone was shown to be a pigment stone.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f13b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g14x.jpeg" height="1584" width="1496" aria-labelledby="f14-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> CBD stone. Curved planar reformatted image from CT cholangiographic data obtained with iodipamide meglumine (Cholografin; Bracco Diagnostics, Princeton, NJ) shows dense excreted contrast material outlining a stone (arrow), which has an attenuation similar to that of fluid.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f14-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g15x.jpeg" height="1190" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f15-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Wrap artifact. On a 2D MR cholangiopancreatogram obtained with parallel imaging and a small field of view, some of the high-signal-intensity subcutaneous fat in the anteroposterior direction has been excluded, resulting in extensive wrap artifact (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f15-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g16a.jpeg" height="1284" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f16a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Obscuration of CBD stones. <b>(a)</b> On a full-volume MIP image obtained in a patient with cholelithiasis and choledocholithiasis, no calculi are seen. <b>(b)</b> Subvolume MIP image clearly depicts numerous calculi in the CBD (arrow), findings that are compatible with choledocholithiasis. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#b4-0291669" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b4-0291669">4</a>.) <b>(c, d)</b> Axial 2D MR cholangiopancreatograms (<b>d</b> obtained caudad to <b>c</b>) show multiple filling defects in the CBD (arrow), findings that correspond to the calculi seen in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f16a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g16b.jpeg" height="1296" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f16b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Obscuration of CBD stones. <b>(a)</b> On a full-volume MIP image obtained in a patient with cholelithiasis and choledocholithiasis, no calculi are seen. <b>(b)</b> Subvolume MIP image clearly depicts numerous calculi in the CBD (arrow), findings that are compatible with choledocholithiasis. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#b4-0291669" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b4-0291669">4</a>.) <b>(c, d)</b> Axial 2D MR cholangiopancreatograms (<b>d</b> obtained caudad to <b>c</b>) show multiple filling defects in the CBD (arrow), findings that correspond to the calculi seen in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f16b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16c-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g16c.jpeg" height="1312" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f16c-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> Obscuration of CBD stones. <b>(a)</b> On a full-volume MIP image obtained in a patient with cholelithiasis and choledocholithiasis, no calculi are seen. <b>(b)</b> Subvolume MIP image clearly depicts numerous calculi in the CBD (arrow), findings that are compatible with choledocholithiasis. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#b4-0291669" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b4-0291669">4</a>.) <b>(c, d)</b> Axial 2D MR cholangiopancreatograms (<b>d</b> obtained caudad to <b>c</b>) show multiple filling defects in the CBD (arrow), findings that correspond to the calculi seen in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f16c-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16d-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g16d.jpeg" height="1302" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f16d-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16d</span> Obscuration of CBD stones. <b>(a)</b> On a full-volume MIP image obtained in a patient with cholelithiasis and choledocholithiasis, no calculi are seen. <b>(b)</b> Subvolume MIP image clearly depicts numerous calculi in the CBD (arrow), findings that are compatible with choledocholithiasis. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#b4-0291669" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b4-0291669">4</a>.) <b>(c, d)</b> Axial 2D MR cholangiopancreatograms (<b>d</b> obtained caudad to <b>c</b>) show multiple filling defects in the CBD (arrow), findings that correspond to the calculi seen in <b>b</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f16d-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f17a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g17a.jpeg" height="1306" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f17a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Two-dimensional vs 3D MR cholangiopancreatography in a patient with a distal CBD stricture. Two-dimensional thick-slab (5-cm) single-shot RARE MR cholangiopancreatogram <b>(a)</b> and collapsed MIP image from 3D MR cholangiopancreatographic data obtained at 3.0 T <b>(b)</b> show improved visualization of the IBDs at 3D MR cholangiopancreatography.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f17a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f17b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g17b.jpeg" height="1313" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f17b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Two-dimensional vs 3D MR cholangiopancreatography in a patient with a distal CBD stricture. Two-dimensional thick-slab (5-cm) single-shot RARE MR cholangiopancreatogram <b>(a)</b> and collapsed MIP image from 3D MR cholangiopancreatographic data obtained at 3.0 T <b>(b)</b> show improved visualization of the IBDs at 3D MR cholangiopancreatography.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f17b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g18a.jpeg" height="1547" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f18a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> <b>(a, b)</b> Axial Gd-EOB-DTPA–enhanced 3D gradient-echo source MR images (<b>b</b> obtained caudad to <b>a</b>) show contrast material in the normal left and right hepatic ducts. <b>(c)</b> MIP reformatted image shows the contrast-enhanced bile ducts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f18a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g18b.jpeg" height="1548" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f18b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> <b>(a, b)</b> Axial Gd-EOB-DTPA–enhanced 3D gradient-echo source MR images (<b>b</b> obtained caudad to <b>a</b>) show contrast material in the normal left and right hepatic ducts. <b>(c)</b> MIP reformatted image shows the contrast-enhanced bile ducts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f18b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18c-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g18c.jpeg" height="1298" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f18c-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span> <b>(a, b)</b> Axial Gd-EOB-DTPA–enhanced 3D gradient-echo source MR images (<b>b</b> obtained caudad to <b>a</b>) show contrast material in the normal left and right hepatic ducts. <b>(c)</b> MIP reformatted image shows the contrast-enhanced bile ducts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f18c-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g19a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1746" aria-labelledby="f19a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> Biliary leak following cholecystectomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial 3D gradient-echo T1-weighted source MR image obtained 20 minutes after Gd-EOB-DTPA injection shows minimal contrast material leakage (arrowhead) into the gallbladder fossa. <b>(b, c)</b> On axial source images obtained 8 hours after injection, the amount of leaked contrast material has increased significantly (arrowheads) and appears to be arising from the region of the cystic duct stump (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> MIP image shows the contrast-enhanced bile ducts and extraluminal contrast material (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f19a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g19b.jpeg" height="1321" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f19b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> Biliary leak following cholecystectomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial 3D gradient-echo T1-weighted source MR image obtained 20 minutes after Gd-EOB-DTPA injection shows minimal contrast material leakage (arrowhead) into the gallbladder fossa. <b>(b, c)</b> On axial source images obtained 8 hours after injection, the amount of leaked contrast material has increased significantly (arrowheads) and appears to be arising from the region of the cystic duct stump (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> MIP image shows the contrast-enhanced bile ducts and extraluminal contrast material (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f19b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19c-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g19c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1743" aria-labelledby="f19c-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span> Biliary leak following cholecystectomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial 3D gradient-echo T1-weighted source MR image obtained 20 minutes after Gd-EOB-DTPA injection shows minimal contrast material leakage (arrowhead) into the gallbladder fossa. <b>(b, c)</b> On axial source images obtained 8 hours after injection, the amount of leaked contrast material has increased significantly (arrowheads) and appears to be arising from the region of the cystic duct stump (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> MIP image shows the contrast-enhanced bile ducts and extraluminal contrast material (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f19c-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f19d-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g19d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1776" aria-labelledby="f19d-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19d</span> Biliary leak following cholecystectomy. <b>(a)</b> Axial 3D gradient-echo T1-weighted source MR image obtained 20 minutes after Gd-EOB-DTPA injection shows minimal contrast material leakage (arrowhead) into the gallbladder fossa. <b>(b, c)</b> On axial source images obtained 8 hours after injection, the amount of leaked contrast material has increased significantly (arrowheads) and appears to be arising from the region of the cystic duct stump (arrow in <b>c</b>). <b>(d)</b> MIP image shows the contrast-enhanced bile ducts and extraluminal contrast material (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f19d-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f20a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g20a.jpeg" height="1527" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f20a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> <b>(a)</b> Axial CT cholangiogram obtained in a living potential liver donor shows the excretion of intravenous iodipamide meglumine into the biliary tract and opacification of the thin, normal-caliber bile ducts (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal 3D VR image allows visualization of the anatomy of the bile duct and cystic duct.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f20a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f20b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24c20b.jpeg" height="1069" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f20b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> <b>(a)</b> Axial CT cholangiogram obtained in a living potential liver donor shows the excretion of intravenous iodipamide meglumine into the biliary tract and opacification of the thin, normal-caliber bile ducts (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal 3D VR image allows visualization of the anatomy of the bile duct and cystic duct.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f20b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f21-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g21x.jpeg" height="1285" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f21-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Coronal CT cholangiogram obtained in a patient who had undergone cholecystectomy shows an unopacified CBD (arrowhead) in the head of the pancreas. Leakage of excreted biliary contrast material (arrow) is seen arising from a location superior to the inadvertently ligated CBD. The leak was not identified at ERCP because the CHD failed to opacify.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f21-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f22a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g22a.jpeg" height="1593" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f22a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> Comparison of imaging methods for evaluation of a Klatskin tumor. <b>(a)</b> Thick-slab (5-cm) single-shot RARE heavily T2-weighted MR image shows abrupt obstruction at the confluence of the left and right main hepatic ducts (arrow) and no evidence of CBD dilatation. The image does not show the tumor directly. <b>(b)</b> Coronal thin-section single-shot RARE image more clearly depicts the cross-sectional anatomy of the bile ducts as well as the intermediate-signal-intensity tumor (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Coronal 2-cm-thick subvolume minimum-intensity-projection image from contrast-enhanced CT data shows dilated IBDs and the surrounding anatomy but does not show the tumor well (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f22a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f22b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g22b.jpeg" height="1610" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f22b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> Comparison of imaging methods for evaluation of a Klatskin tumor. <b>(a)</b> Thick-slab (5-cm) single-shot RARE heavily T2-weighted MR image shows abrupt obstruction at the confluence of the left and right main hepatic ducts (arrow) and no evidence of CBD dilatation. The image does not show the tumor directly. <b>(b)</b> Coronal thin-section single-shot RARE image more clearly depicts the cross-sectional anatomy of the bile ducts as well as the intermediate-signal-intensity tumor (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Coronal 2-cm-thick subvolume minimum-intensity-projection image from contrast-enhanced CT data shows dilated IBDs and the surrounding anatomy but does not show the tumor well (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f22b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f22c-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g22c.jpeg" height="1374" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f22c-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22c</span> Comparison of imaging methods for evaluation of a Klatskin tumor. <b>(a)</b> Thick-slab (5-cm) single-shot RARE heavily T2-weighted MR image shows abrupt obstruction at the confluence of the left and right main hepatic ducts (arrow) and no evidence of CBD dilatation. The image does not show the tumor directly. <b>(b)</b> Coronal thin-section single-shot RARE image more clearly depicts the cross-sectional anatomy of the bile ducts as well as the intermediate-signal-intensity tumor (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Coronal 2-cm-thick subvolume minimum-intensity-projection image from contrast-enhanced CT data shows dilated IBDs and the surrounding anatomy but does not show the tumor well (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f22c-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f23a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g23a.jpeg" height="1518" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f23a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> MIP vs minimum intensity projection in a patient with a Klatskin tumor. MIP reformatted image from 3D T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data <b>(a)</b> and minimum-intensity-projection reformatted image from 3D gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data <b>(b)</b> show a long stricture of the CHD and the confluence of the left and right hepatic ducts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f23a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f23b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g23b.jpeg" height="1487" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f23b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> MIP vs minimum intensity projection in a patient with a Klatskin tumor. MIP reformatted image from 3D T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data <b>(a)</b> and minimum-intensity-projection reformatted image from 3D gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data <b>(b)</b> show a long stricture of the CHD and the confluence of the left and right hepatic ducts.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f23b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f24a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g24a.jpeg" height="1302" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f24a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span> On MIP <b>(a)</b> and VR <b>(b)</b> images from 3D RARE T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data obtained in a patient with a Klatskin tumor, the latter image better demonstrates a stricture and markedly dilated IBDs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f24a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f24b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g24b.jpeg" height="1321" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f24b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span> On MIP <b>(a)</b> and VR <b>(b)</b> images from 3D RARE T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data obtained in a patient with a Klatskin tumor, the latter image better demonstrates a stricture and markedly dilated IBDs.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f24b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g02a.jpeg" height="1455" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f2a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> <b>(a)</b> On an MIP image from 3D rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement (RARE) T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data obtained at 1.5 T, the IBDs can be visualized to the third- and fourth-order branches. <b>(b)</b> MIP image from 3D RARE T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data obtained in a different patient at 3.0 T again depicts the IBDs to the third- and fourth-order branches. Note how the fluid in the duodenum (arrow) obscures the low insertion of the right posterior hepatic duct on the CHD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f2a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g02b.jpeg" height="1411" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f2b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> <b>(a)</b> On an MIP image from 3D rapid acquisition with relaxation enhancement (RARE) T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data obtained at 1.5 T, the IBDs can be visualized to the third- and fourth-order branches. <b>(b)</b> MIP image from 3D RARE T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data obtained in a different patient at 3.0 T again depicts the IBDs to the third- and fourth-order branches. Note how the fluid in the duodenum (arrow) obscures the low insertion of the right posterior hepatic duct on the CHD.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f2b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g03a.jpeg" height="1343" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Malignant CHD stricture. <b>(a, b)</b> Radial thick-slab (4-cm) <b>(a)</b> and coronal thin-section (4-mm) <b>(b)</b> single-shot RARE MR cholangiopancreatograms show a long stricture of the CHD (arrow) and mild dilatation of the IBDs. The thin, hyperintense line across the stricture represents fluid in a biliary stent. <b>(c)</b> On an axial thin-section single-shot RARE MR cholangiopancreatogram, the stent (arrowhead) is seen as a small filling defect in the dilated CHD upstream from the stricture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f3a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g03b.jpeg" height="1322" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Malignant CHD stricture. <b>(a, b)</b> Radial thick-slab (4-cm) <b>(a)</b> and coronal thin-section (4-mm) <b>(b)</b> single-shot RARE MR cholangiopancreatograms show a long stricture of the CHD (arrow) and mild dilatation of the IBDs. The thin, hyperintense line across the stricture represents fluid in a biliary stent. <b>(c)</b> On an axial thin-section single-shot RARE MR cholangiopancreatogram, the stent (arrowhead) is seen as a small filling defect in the dilated CHD upstream from the stricture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f3b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3c-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g03c.jpeg" height="1132" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3c-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Malignant CHD stricture. <b>(a, b)</b> Radial thick-slab (4-cm) <b>(a)</b> and coronal thin-section (4-mm) <b>(b)</b> single-shot RARE MR cholangiopancreatograms show a long stricture of the CHD (arrow) and mild dilatation of the IBDs. The thin, hyperintense line across the stricture represents fluid in a biliary stent. <b>(c)</b> On an axial thin-section single-shot RARE MR cholangiopancreatogram, the stent (arrowhead) is seen as a small filling defect in the dilated CHD upstream from the stricture.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f3c-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g04x.jpeg" height="1400" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f4-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Double duct sign. MIP image from 3D T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data shows a pancreatic carcinoma that causes upstream pancreatic dilatation (arrow), including main and side branch ductal dilatation, along with CBD obstruction (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f4-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g05a.jpeg" height="1361" width="1566" aria-labelledby="f5a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Cholangiocarcinoma. <i>P</i> = portal vein. <b>(a)</b> Portal venous phase intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan through the liver shows an ill-defined hilar mass (arrow) that causes IBD obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Delayed CT scan obtained 15 minutes after intravenous contrast material administration more clearly depicts the margins of the mass (arrow), which proved to be a cholangiocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f5a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g05b.jpeg" height="1385" width="1584" aria-labelledby="f5b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Cholangiocarcinoma. <i>P</i> = portal vein. <b>(a)</b> Portal venous phase intravenous contrast-enhanced CT scan through the liver shows an ill-defined hilar mass (arrow) that causes IBD obstruction. <b>(b)</b> Delayed CT scan obtained 15 minutes after intravenous contrast material administration more clearly depicts the margins of the mass (arrow), which proved to be a cholangiocarcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f5b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g06a.jpeg" height="1110" width="1170" aria-labelledby="f6a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Portal biliopathy. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows portal vein collateral vessels (arrow) and mild IBD dilatation (arrow-heads). <b>(b)</b> ERCP image obtained 3 days later because of an elevated serum bilirubin level shows mass effect exerted by the engorged portal vein collateral vessels on the CBD (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f6a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g06b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1259" aria-labelledby="f6b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Portal biliopathy. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows portal vein collateral vessels (arrow) and mild IBD dilatation (arrow-heads). <b>(b)</b> ERCP image obtained 3 days later because of an elevated serum bilirubin level shows mass effect exerted by the engorged portal vein collateral vessels on the CBD (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f6b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g07a.jpeg" height="1371" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Inadvertent ligation of the right IBD at cholecystectomy. <b>(a)</b> Thick-slab (5-cm) MR cholangiopancreatogram shows dilatation of the right IBD (arrow) upstream from a ductal stricture. The left IBD, CHD, and CBD are normal. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> thin-section (5-mm) single-shot RARE MR cholangiopancreatograms demonstrate an abrupt obstruction of the right IBD (arrowhead), which was accidentally ligated during laparoscopic cholecystectomy. The signal void at the point of obstruction is caused by susceptibility artifact from surgical clips.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f7a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g07b.jpeg" height="1512" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Inadvertent ligation of the right IBD at cholecystectomy. <b>(a)</b> Thick-slab (5-cm) MR cholangiopancreatogram shows dilatation of the right IBD (arrow) upstream from a ductal stricture. The left IBD, CHD, and CBD are normal. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> thin-section (5-mm) single-shot RARE MR cholangiopancreatograms demonstrate an abrupt obstruction of the right IBD (arrowhead), which was accidentally ligated during laparoscopic cholecystectomy. The signal void at the point of obstruction is caused by susceptibility artifact from surgical clips.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f7b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7c-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g07c.jpeg" height="1286" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7c-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Inadvertent ligation of the right IBD at cholecystectomy. <b>(a)</b> Thick-slab (5-cm) MR cholangiopancreatogram shows dilatation of the right IBD (arrow) upstream from a ductal stricture. The left IBD, CHD, and CBD are normal. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> thin-section (5-mm) single-shot RARE MR cholangiopancreatograms demonstrate an abrupt obstruction of the right IBD (arrowhead), which was accidentally ligated during laparoscopic cholecystectomy. The signal void at the point of obstruction is caused by susceptibility artifact from surgical clips.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f7c-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g08a.jpeg" height="1242" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f8a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Artifactual pseudostricture from cholecystectomy clips. <b>(a)</b> On an MIP image from 3D respiratory-gated RARE T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data, portions of the CHD cannot be visualized (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial opposed-phase T1-weighted MR image shows hypointense foci around the CBD (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> In-phase image obtained with a longer echo time shows blooming artifact (arrowheads) caused by adjacent metallic cholecystectomy clips.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f8a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g08b.jpeg" height="1322" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f8b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Artifactual pseudostricture from cholecystectomy clips. <b>(a)</b> On an MIP image from 3D respiratory-gated RARE T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data, portions of the CHD cannot be visualized (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial opposed-phase T1-weighted MR image shows hypointense foci around the CBD (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> In-phase image obtained with a longer echo time shows blooming artifact (arrowheads) caused by adjacent metallic cholecystectomy clips.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f8b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8c-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g08c.jpeg" height="1370" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f8c-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span> Artifactual pseudostricture from cholecystectomy clips. <b>(a)</b> On an MIP image from 3D respiratory-gated RARE T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data, portions of the CHD cannot be visualized (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial opposed-phase T1-weighted MR image shows hypointense foci around the CBD (arrowheads). <b>(c)</b> In-phase image obtained with a longer echo time shows blooming artifact (arrowheads) caused by adjacent metallic cholecystectomy clips.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f8c-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9a-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g09a.jpeg" height="1293" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9a-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Pseudostricture from a crossing hepatic artery. <b>(a)</b> MIP image from 3D respiratory-gated RARE T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data shows focal signal loss in the CHD (arrow) near the porta hepatis. Note also the variant biliary anatomy, with the posterior right hepatic duct inserting into the left hepatic duct (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase contrast-enhanced spoiled gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a crossing right hepatic artery (arrow) near the biliary tree, a finding that corresponds to the pseudonarrowing seen on the MIP image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f9a-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9b-0291669" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095514/asset/images/g09oc24g09b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9b-0291669" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Pseudostricture from a crossing hepatic artery. <b>(a)</b> MIP image from 3D respiratory-gated RARE T2-weighted MR cholangiopancreatographic data shows focal signal loss in the CHD (arrow) near the porta hepatis. Note also the variant biliary anatomy, with the posterior right hepatic duct inserting into the left hepatic duct (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Axial arterial phase contrast-enhanced spoiled gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a crossing right hepatic artery (arrow) near the biliary tree, a finding that corresponds to the pseudonarrowing seen on the MIP image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095514&amp;id=f9b-0291669">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="b1-0291669" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Hekimoglu K, Ustundag Y, Dusak A, et al. MRCP vs. ERCP in the evaluation of biliary pathologies: review of current literature. <em>J Dig Dis</em> 2008;9:162–169.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1751-2980.2008.00339.x">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18956595/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/sc